Setup (One-Time)

First, ensure your personal bin directory exists and is secured from other users:
Bash

mkdir -p $HOME/bin
chmod go-rwx $HOME/bin

Note: If typing echo $PATH does not show your bin directory (e.g., /home/yourusername/bin), you will need to add export PATH="$HOME/bin:$PATH" to your hidden ~/.bashrc or ~/.profile file so the system knows to look there for your scripts.
Exercise: The d Script

This script creates a quick, two-letter shortcut for a detailed file listing, passing along any extra directories or options you type.

    Create and open the file:
    Bash

    nano $HOME/bin/d

    Add the code:
    Bash

    #!/bin/bash
    ls -l $*

    (The #!/bin/bash is called a "shebang." It tells the system exactly which interpreter to use to run the script. While optional for very basic commands, it is a crucial habit for shell scripting).

    Save and exit (In nano, press Ctrl+O to save, Enter to confirm, then Ctrl+X to exit).

    Make the file executable:
    Bash

    chmod +x $HOME/bin/d

    Run it:
    Bash

    d
    d /etc

Exercise: The gnews Script

This script fetches the live HTML of the RTE News homepage and searches for the word you provide.

    Create and open the file:
    Bash

    nano $HOME/bin/gnews

    Add the code:
    Bash

    #!/bin/bash

    # Check if the user actually provided an argument
    if [ -z "$1" ]; then
        echo "Usage: gnews <search_term>"
        exit 1
    fi

    # Fetch the page and search for the term
    # -q makes wget run quietly (no progress bars)
    # -O - tells wget to output the downloaded text directly to the screen (stdout)
    # grep -i makes the search case-insensitive
    wget -q -O - https://www.rte.ie/news/ | grep -i "$1"

    Save and exit.

    Make it executable:
    Bash

    chmod +x $HOME/bin/gnews

    Run it:
    Bash

    gnews Dublin
    gnews weather

    Key insight: Because wget pulls down raw website code, your terminal will print out the actual HTML tags (like <h2> or <a>) surrounding the word you searched for.
